    "summary": "The Battle of Mylae (260 BC) was the first significant Roman naval victory of the [[event:1053|First Punic War]], fought off the northeastern coast of Sicily and remembered primarily for the debut of the corvus — the Roman boarding device that transformed naval combat into something resembling land battle. The Roman consul Gaius Duilius commanded the fleet that defeated a Carthaginian squadron of roughly 130 ships.\n\nRome had built its first major war fleet just months before the battle, training crews on oars while ships were still under construction. The corvus was a pole with a spiked bridge that could be dropped onto an enemy deck, latching on and allowing Roman marines to board and fight in the close-quarters combat in which they excelled. At Mylae, the Romans used the corvus to capture or sink fifty Carthaginian ships while losing almost none of their own. Duilius was awarded a triumph in Rome — the first naval triumph in Roman history — commemorated by a column decorated with ship's rams (rostra) in the Forum, a monument still partially visible today. The battle proved that Rome could compete at sea, a prerequisite for winning the Sicilian war.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Mylae",
